enrichment.summary: This executive order establishes the Interagency Security Committee to improve and oversee the security of federal buildings and facilities occupied by federal employees and contractors. It sets policies, standards, and compliance measures to ensure effective protection and coordination across various federal agencies.
potential_concerns: Enhanced interagency security coordination may lead to increased surveillance and data sharing that could raise privacy concerns among federal employees and contractors.
Strict security standards and compliance requirements could impose operational burdens and increased costs on federal contractors, potentially impacting contract performance and worker conditions.

The focus on blast-resistant structures and specialized facility security may divert resources from other federal buildings, potentially creating uneven security protections across different federal employee work sites.
Coordination in multi-agency, multi-use facilities might lead to jurisdictional conflicts or slowed decision-making affecting the safety and daily workflow of federal employees and contractors.
